<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-146-682  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 146 682.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 12 1990 v24 n7 p90(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Quality through documentation. (William E. Perry of the QualityAssurance Institute) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Maglitta, Joseph.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>William E. Perry, executive director of the Quality AssuranceInstitute of Orlando, FL, estimates that because of poor softwaredocumentation, 70 percent of the average information systems (IS)budget goes for rework and only 30 percent goes for productivework.andP;  A scientific approach has to be applied to softwaredocumentation.andP;  The federal government's emphasis on softwaredocumentation is growing because of defense cuts and the poorsoftware the government is receiving.andP;  Organizations canstandardize the process of documenting software changes andinstall a continuous, measurable improvement program.andP;  Thecultural change is the hardest part of such an effort.andP;  Thebiggest problem with software maintenance is that most ISdirectors feel they are already doing a good job.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     InterviewQuality Assurance InstituteDocumentationSoftware maintenanceManagement of EDPPlanning.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   William E. Perry. (portrait)Person:    Perry, William E. (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>